title: At least four dead in Philippines after super typhoon makes landfall | ABC NEWS
description: At least four people have died, and over 1.4 million have been displaced after Super Typhoon Fung-Wong struck the Philippines.  This powerful storm has brought sustained winds of 185 km/h and heavy rain, prompting warnings for flash flooding and landslides in the northern region of Luzon. title: Top BBC bosses resign over edit of Donald Trump documentary | ABC NEWS
description: The BBC's director-general and head of news have resigned amid criticism of the broadcaster's editing of a speech Donald Trump delivered before protesters attacked the US Capitol. Critics said the edit was misleading and cut out a section where Mr Trump said he wanted supporters to demonstrate peacefully. Mr Trump has reacted, saying those who "doctored" his speech were "very dishonest people who tried to step on the scales of a presidential election". title: Mass fish kill at Tassal barramundi farm in WA's Cone Bay | ABC NEWS
description: Aquaculture company Tassal faced a recent fish kill at its barramundi farms in Cone Bay, Western Australia, due to a parasite and stress from low temperatures. title: Death toll rises after Super Typhoon Fung-wong slams into the Philippines | The World | ABC NEWS
description: One of the year's most powerful storms in the Philippines, Super Typhoon Fung-wong has killed four people, as authorities begin assessing damage. title: Thousands of flights cancelled in US amid government shutdown | The World | ABC NEWS
description: As the US senate votes in favour of a bill which would see the end of the longest government shutdown in the country's history, the aviation industry has taken a massive hit. Hundreds of thousands of travellers have been affected by flight cancellations and delays. Steven Leib, senior lecturer in aviation at CQ University, told The World the industry is hopeful that schedule and staffing issues will get back on track ahead of the Thanksgiving holiday season. title: China's rising obsession with amateur soccer matches | The World | ABC NEWS
description: Amateur soccer leagues in China have seen a surge in popularity in recent years, often drawing crowds to rival professional matches. China has the largest number of soccer fans in the world, but its top league has struggled with a history of corruption and match-fixing. Now, a grassroots movement organised by workers and students is hoping to breathe new life into the sport. Rebecca Johnston reports.
